The Spanish and Russian translated newsletter for this issue will be available soon.

June 6 at 2:43 AM · Woodburn, OR ·

French Prairie Middle School - 2020 8th Grade Promotion

Congratulations French Prairie Middle School 8th grade class for completing one journey and commencing another. French Prairie Middle School (FPMS) 8th grade promotion was held as a drive-through celebration this year at Woodburn High School, June 4, 2020. Practicing social distancing, FPMS staff and administrators gathered at the high school to present student’s with 8th grade promotion certificates and to say goodbye for the summer. ( Please note that these photos were shot using a telephoto, thus keeping requirements of social distance.) Photo by Rick Vasquez/Woodburn School District

Dear Woodburn School District Families,

The Woodburn School District will move forward with the cost saving strategy of implementing a staff furlough day once a week. The first furlough day will be this Monday, May 18th. This will be a non-work day for staff so there will be no Distance Learning sessions for students. Students may use the day for catching up, research, wellness activities, reading, or other activities they enjoy. Distance Learning will resume Tuesday through Friday. Meals will not be available on Monday, but extra meals will be provided on Friday to support students through Monday. Thank you for helping to support this cost saving measure which will help with anticipated budget shortfalls next year.

post_text:
The following message has been sent via email and robocall this evening:
March 31, 2020
Hello Woodburn School District Families,

During this time of school closure, we are thinking about you, and hope that this message finds you and your family safe and healthy. We miss you. We are calling to let you know that a staff member from your child’s school will be calling you this week to check in, see how you are, and learn about how we can best support your student’s out of school learning. Here is what you need to know about your call:
-It may come from an unfamiliar number, or show as “no caller ID” on your phone. Please answer it anyway.
-If you are not available when we call, we will leave a voicemail with a time when we will try to call again.

When we call, we will want to know:
-How you are doing and feeling
-If your student is able to access meals
-If your student has access to the internet, a phone, and a device such as a laptop.

We look forward to connecting with you soon. Until then, stay healthy and safe! Thank you.

post_text:
March 17, 2020
Dear Woodburn School Community,

Thank you for your patience during these challenging times.
This evening, March 17th, Governor Kate Brown ordered that public schools are to remain closed to students from March 16, 2020, through April 28, 2020, unless that period is extended or ended earlier by the Governor.

We know this creates a hardship on our entire community and we will be communicating very soon on how we will work to support the continuation of the educational and support services provided by our schools.

We will be receiving further guidance from the Oregon Department of Education tomorrow and we will continue to provide further details and updates for you as this information becomes available. Our guidance continues to be informed by The Oregon Health Authority, The Oregon Department of Health and Human Services, and by the Oregon Department of Education.

Thanks again for all you do to support our school community and please check regularly for updates.

With Spirit,
Bill

Woodburn School Community:

Following the latest guidance from Gov. Brown, Woodburn School District will be closed for students from Monday, March 16 through Tuesday, March 31st. Students will return to school on April 1st.

During the closure, all school-based sports and extracurricular activities will also be canceled.

Woodburn School District staff will provide free grab-and-go meals to ages 1 - 18 from 9:00 AM- 12:00 PM at the following locations: Washington Elementary, Nuevo Amenecer and French Prairie Middle School. (See flyer)

Woodburn School District will continue to monitor the situation in conjunction with state agencies and will provide updates during the extended break.

post_text:
Will Woodburn see snow next week? ❄️☃️🤔

Just in case... here is some information regarding alerts and messages we send out to parents/guardians and the community if we have an inclement weather delay or closure:

-Email or SMS text: Parents/guardians will receive an email and/or SMS text message. Please note, you have to be subscribed to receive texts and we must have your updated email address on file. Please call your school office if you have any questions or need to update your information.

-Website: we will post current status and updated information on our homepage.

-FlashAlert: FlashAlert is where TV, newspapers and other media receive our status via email. FlashAlert is also available to the public. Subscribe here for Woodburn Sch. Dist. http://www.flashalert.net/news.html?id=213 or download the App on your smart phone to receive an instant notification.

-Facebook: 'Like' this page and follow us!

post_text: Thank you, Woodburn PD for helping us keep our students, staff and families safe.
shared_text:
City of Woodburn
August 30, 2019 at 5:00 PM ·

Back to school means be alert!

The Woodburn Police Department will conduct traffic safety enforcement during the beginning of the school year, starting Tuesday, September 3 through Friday, September 13, 2019. This will take place throughout all Woodburn School Zones.

Officers will be focusing on enforcing speed, seat belt usage, unlawful use of mobile devices while driving and any other unsafe driving violations. The goal of traffic safety enforcement is to keep students, school staff and community members safe during this school season. WPD wants to remind everyone that most school zones in Woodburn have reduced school speed zone laws of 20 miles per hour between 7:00 a.m. and 5:00 p.m. on all school days, and that traffic violations in these zones face enhanced fine amounts.

#BeAlert
#BackToSchool2019

We are so proud of tonight's graduating class but we have a few reminders and information if you plan on attending.

-Gates open at 3:30 pm
-Seating is first come, first served

-Please keep balloons and umbrellas under your seat (be considerate of people behind you)
-No standing in front of seated guests
-Rain or shine graduation will continue, please plan accordingly
Thank you!

If you have any additional questions, please contact your school office directly.

NEWS RELEASE: The Woodburn School Board unanimously passed a resolution asking the state legislature to adequately fund education. The resolution states that Oregon’s public schools have experienced a long period of unstable and inadequate funding that has resulted in teacher and staff layoffs, program cuts, larger class sizes, and a shorter school year.

Oregon lawmakers are feeling pressure from school districts as part of the Oregonians for Student Success campaign sponsored by the state school board association. School board members and other education groups are advocating for funding at the Quality Education Model (QEM) level estimated at $10.734 billion.

To read more...

Congratulations to Academy of International Studies student BELEN CORTES! This morning she was announced (and surprised) as the 2019 Distinguished Service Alma Awards YOUTH OF THE YEAR. DSAA is a sponsored event by the Woodburn Area Chamber of Commerce. Belen will officially receive her award and be celebrated at the DSAA banquet on March 8, 2019.

Belen is an Junior at AIS, a member of the National Honor Society and Key Club President. In addition, she spends her time volunteering in a community garden project (that donates food to AWARE), Battle of the Books, Love Santa, Kiwanis, blood drives, voter registration and STEM festival to name a few. Thank you Belen for being a leader in our community!

Woodburn School District added 3 new photos.
January 9, 2019 at 11:48 PM ·

The high school building for the Success High School was opened for the 2018-19 school year. It was built adjacent to the Welcome Center/District Office on Meridian Drive. The community was invited to a celebration and Grand Opening on Thursday, September 27, 2018 at 6:30 p.m. The Success High School site includes a solar array that provides power for the school, as well as educational opportunities. The school is a net-zero for energy consumption, meaning it produces more energy that it uses. You can view the solar output at an online kiosk to track energy produced by day, week, month, year or lifetime! View the kiosk at http://kiosk.datareadings.com/GjgTn4Se/overview?granularity=month

post_text: Late Sunday evening we were made aware of a threat made against French Prairie Middle school through the SafeOregon tip line, an online resource where students and families can anonymously report unsafe behavior in schools. The Woodburn Police Department began immediately investigating and early this morning, after contacting the parties involved, were able to determine there is no threat to FPMS. Our top priority is the safety of our students and staff. School will continue as scheduled.

post_text:
The Woodburn School Board is proud to announce the appointment of Noemi Legaspi to fill the vacant seat on its board. Her term runs until June 2019. The position will be elected by the community on the ballot in May next year.

Additionally, the School Board has appointed four new members to committees. Thor Waage and Chris Lassen will serve on the Bond Advisory and Accountability Committee until bond-funded projects are complete. John Rivas and Christopher Branger will each serve a 3-year term (June 2021) on the Budget Committee.

Thank you all for your service and dedication to our students and school district!
text:
The Woodburn School Board is proud to announce the appointment of Noemi Legaspi to fill the vacant seat on its board. Her term runs until June 2019. The position will be elected by the community on the ballot in May next year.

Additionally, the School Board has appointed four new members to committees. Thor Waage and Chris Lassen will serve on the Bond Advisory and Accountability Committee until bond-funded projects are complete. John Rivas and Christopher Branger will each serve a 3-year term (June 2021) on the Budget Committee.

Thank you all for your service and dedication to our students and school district!

Did you know that volunteering can be beneficial to your health? According to Harvard Health Publications, "“There’s a growing body of research showing that volunteering is associated with better physical and mental health outcomes,” says Eric S. If you're interested in volunteering for the Woodburn School District, please visit our website to view a few openings at http://www.woodburnsd.org/blog/2018/10/168434/. Thank you for considering!

post_text:
Woodburn High School Theatre is proud to announce their upcoming production of the contemporary play Black Butterfly, Jaguar Girl, Pinata Woman and Other Superhero Girls, Like Me by Luis Alfaro. The production opens November 9.

The show runs for two weekends, Friday-Saturday, November 9-10 and 16-17, at 7:00 pm. All performances take place at the Woodburn High School Auditorium. Tickets are $5 for general admission. Tickets can be purchased from the box office starting thirty minutes before each performance.

For more information or for group seating reservations, please contact Caleb Thurston (cthurston@woodburnsd.org; 503-980-6275.)

For the first time in nearly 50 years, the Woodburn football team is playoff bound. Quarterback R.J. Veliz scored a touchdown with 1:07 remaining to put the Bulldogs up 18-13, and kicker Cole Beyer recovered a fumble on the ensuing kickoff to seal the victory.

Woodburn (6-3, 2-3 SD2) will open the first round at No. 5 Mazama (6-1, 4-0SD5) on Friday.
